{"timestamp": "2025-12-12 19:56:35.523923", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: The ping results show that all hosts can reach each other, but the round‑trip times are wildly inconsistent – some hops show a few milliseconds of jitter, while others swing from 1\\u202fms to 6\\u202fms or more.  \\nThat pattern is exactly what you see when a switch (or a set of switches) is doing **per‑packet load‑balancing** (or “hash‑per‑packet” forwarding).  \\n\\nIn this topology the P4 switch is configured to hash on the packet header for every packet that it forwards. Because the hash changes from packet to packet, the switch may forward the two packets of a ping along **different equal‑cost paths** (e.g., one packet goes via the “fast” link, the next via a longer, congested link). The result is that the two packets of a single ping experience very different delays, which shows up as a high RTT variance in the ping output.\\n\\nSo the high RTT variance is caused by the per‑packet load‑balancing algorithm in the switch, which routes packets on different paths each time., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='2f01f9e6-99ab-4fae-a637-f9671e4385dd'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "not_implemented", "id": ["langchain_ollama", "chat_models", "ChatOllama"], "repr": "ChatOllama(model='gpt-oss:20b', validate_model_on_init=True, temperature=0.0, base_url='http://10.68.186.140:11434')", "name": "ChatOllama"}}
